In 1972, the Marine Technology Society was kind enough to give me its Compass Award.
In accepting that, I could not accept it for myself, but I did accept it in the name of the participants in my bureauships program over 20 odd years.

The names of the persons who had some input or were connected in some way with that program may be of interest, and I would like to read them into the record as I did in that speech, somewhat geographically.
Up in Canada, John Longard of the Defense Research Establishment.
In Cambridge, Massachusetts, Charles Mongan, longtime advisor to the sonar section.
At Woods Hole, Columbus Islin, Ed Smith, Paul Fye, Alan Vine, Fritz Fuglista, Jerry Metcalf, Blackett Hersey, Bud Knott, Bill Cheville, Dick Backus.
to name a few.

On 3 August 1967, that year Dale had received and reprinted and edited forms, letters from

The passing note.
Any description of Dr. H. Hughes Frederick's early classes in oceanography should include the four Argentines who, under Juan Peron, were sent up to study oceanography.
They were Rodolfo Panzarini, later Admiral Panzarini, who retired as head of the Antarctic Institute in Argentina.
Iglesias, I believe his name was Hector, I-G-L-E-S-I-S, Iglesias, who became a naval officer.
Luis Capullo, who became Dr. Capullo,
at Texas A&M and was active in SCORE and IOC and other committees in oceanography in Europe for so long.
And Hector Echebehere, E-T-C-H-E-B-E-H-E-R-E, who became a naval officer and an industrialist in Argentina.

Panzerini established the first oceanographic, or hydrographic, correctly, hydrographic office in the Argentine Navy, and Luis Capura was the chief of that office for a while before he came back to Texas A&M to get his doctorate.

Also in passing, notes should be made of the names of women who have been important in oceanography, beginning with Mary Sears, Dr. Mary Sears, now Woods Hole, retired, who was the sole active assistant to Roger Revelle at the Hydrographic Office during the war.
Then June Petullo, the late June Petullo was long a professor at the University of Oregon at Corvallis.
Also Margaret Robinson at Scripps for her continued long-term waking up of the basithemograph data.
and perhaps more in sentiment because she was a student at Scripps when I was there, Jeannie Clark, the famous girl of fishes and shark research.
Oceanographers of today bow down with a mountain of paperwork and a royal protocol and necessity for taking care of prestige of different activities.
Look back with yearning and longing to the old underwater sound propagation committee chaired by Beckett Hershey.
With no regular meeting places, but always bringing the top people into the field and together for an informal discussion and review of their programs in the morning.
and in the afternoon, usually a determination of the priorities and decisions of the program to be carried out for the rest of the year.
The funding was taken care of by the different aid activities and was not a major portion of the committee's business.
In other words, if Fred Spieth said that he had a vehicle which could pursue a certain type of research better than Lamont,
Fred Spieth, MPL, would go ahead and do it, and Lamont would do something else with its money.

But the ease with which discussions were made and priorities established under this completely informal committee work and the able chairman of Brackett Hersey was a delight to all who remember those meetings.
The nearest thing to it
while the three-day meetings at Our Head Lake in the fisheries area under O.E.
Seti called the Epoch Committee.
With the passing of those days, life has become much less joyous to the oceanographers.
Captain T.K.
Treadmill at Texas A&M and others should be questioned for the history of the development of the oceanographic class of ships which the Navy built.

Early after the war, a relatively large number of small military ships were converted for use by the laboratories, beginning with the San Pablo and the Rehoboth, the converted seaplane tenders of the Hydrographic Office.
The funding of the conversions, the choice of the ships, the priorities given to work,

And the final design and building of oceanographic vessels by the Navy itself, the AGOR class, should be looked into very carefully because it was, while the money lasted, a very important vehicle means of getting the oceanographers to sea.
And it permitted the multi-ship operation
investigations which became so important later on in the International Geophysical Year and other efforts of that kind.
A somewhat unique cruise stemming directly from the World War II type of research was the Madea Expedition.

in which oceanographers and acousticians and their acoustic laboratories under the direction of Bob Frasch at the then existing Hudson Laboratories of the University of Columbia, New York, combined the talents of two great groups and the gathering of the information each needed.

Any history should cover the expeditions of the 1950s and 60s with as much interest and accurate detail as has been given to the Challenger, the Meteor, and the other classical expeditions in the past.
It is with great pride that I read into this record in passing

to see what my pride at having such attendance and what it meant to me.
Another tidbit before I forget it.
I can state on personal knowledge that the true developer and the true inventor
Now the expendable bathy thermograph, which is now used in such great quantities, was due to the work of Jim Snodgrass at Scripps.
This and many other things he has contributed as a story all of its own, but in this particular case,

there was on record a letter which I once wrote him asking why we couldn't develop a sinking device which would be picked up by a surface-towed acoustic receiver which would give the temperature at the different depths as the device sank.
And Snodgrass came back with the

information that the signal noise due to water transmission was so great that what we should use would be a wire which would give a connection to the power unit that was sinking or the signaling unit that was sinking.
Sometime later,
Mr. Graham, I believe his name is.
And I had a calendar reference memo of it, visited the bureauships, and forced that they can.
And I said, go see Jim Snodgrass.
They went out to see Jim Snodgrass.
O&R, through some mishap, had lost Snodgrass's patent application.
And as the thing worked out, the Supercarrying Company won the suit for patent rights on the expandable bathymograph.
But all of that happened after Jim Snodgrass had interviewed them and told them of his idea
This is the way I see it and the way I believe it truly happened.

Likewise, another milestone instrument development was due and accredited to BUSHIP's funding on the original report from Morris Ewing's Lamont.
Dorothy Geological Observatory.
Under Ewing's direction, Bernard Ruskin developed the Precision Depth Recorder, incorporating Ewing's original ideas of a tuning fork control of frequency.
The ship's generators varied so much that the

The distance measurement deduced from the time measurement was an error, but by using a tuning fork and developing the recorder which Leskin and Ewing developed, they were able to get the precision to something like six feet out of 18,000.
and was the beginning of the accurate bottom mapping which has come out so beautifully in the interpretations of Bruce Hazen who was at Lamont.
Stop.
One more word.
The precision graphic recorder developed at Woods Hole using a different type of recording paper and being programmed
in order to get recordings from different regions and layers of the water column, also received bureauship's funding, but has always been claimed as an ONR development.
However, the precision depth recorder of Luskin and Ewing preceded the one developed by Hersey and Brednott at Woods Hole.
